Differences in self-similarity by wallpaper group

Purpose

This document summarizes Rick Gilmores analysis of participant sorting data.

Set-up

Analysis plan

  1. Did the wallpaper groups differ in terms of the number of sets into which exemplars were sorted? For example, Vedak et al., 2015 suggested that P1 exemplars were sorted into fewer sets.

  2. Were there differences in mean Jaccard indices by wallpaper group?

  3. Are there wallpaper groups with exemplar pairs that have especially high Jaccard indices?

Import data

N sets

The N sets data are found in analysis/data/nsets.csv.

nsets <- readr::read_csv("analysis/data/nsets.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   Participant = col_character(),
##   Set = col_double(),
##   Nsets = col_double(),
##   Group = col_character()
## )

There are \(n=\) 33 individual participants.

Jaccard indices

The Jaccard index data are found in analysis/data/jaccard.csv.

jaccard <- readr::read_csv("analysis/data/jaccard.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   Exemplar.Row = col_double(),
##   Exemplar.Col = col_double(),
##   Jaccard = col_double(),
##   Group = col_character()
## )

N sets data

Visualizations

N exemplars per set

Lets view the number of exemplars per set per participant. That is, each dot in the plot below is one set contributed by one participant.

exemplars_per_set_plot <- nsets %>%
  ggplot(.) +
  aes(x = Nsets, fill = Group) +
  geom_dotplot(method="histodot", dotsize = 1, binwidth = 1) +
  facet_grid(. ~ Group ) +
  xlab("Set size")
exemplars_per_set_plot

N sets/participant and group

We can also calculate the number of sets per participant and wallpaper group.

nsets_participant <- nsets %>%
  dplyr::group_by(., Participant, Group) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(., nsets_per = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Participant'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
nsets_participant_plot <- nsets_participant %>%
  ggplot(.) +
  aes(x = nsets_per, fill = Group) +
  geom_dotplot(method="histodot", dotsize = 1.5, binwidth = 1) +
  facet_grid(. ~ Group ) +
  xlab("N sets")
nsets_participant_plot

Jaccard index data

Visualizations

jaccard_plot_1 <- jaccard %>%
  ggplot(.) +
  aes(x = Jaccard, fill = Group) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_grid(. ~ Group)
jaccard_plot_1
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value
## with `binwidth`.

jaccard_plot_2 <- jaccard %>%
  ggplot(.) +
  aes(x = Jaccard, fill = Group) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_grid(Group ~ .)
jaccard_plot_2

The mean Jaccard similarity indices across the exemplars was higher for P1; however, note the outliers.

Jaccard outliers

It may be useful to examine those exemplar pairs that have especially large Jaccard indices.

As a starting point for exploration, we examine those exemplars with Jaccard indices > some threshold. Here, we choose 0.35.

jaccard_plot_4 <- jaccard %>%
  filter(., Jaccard > j_thresh) %>%
  ggplot(.) +
  aes(x = Jaccard, fill = Group) +
  geom_boxplot()
jaccard_plot_4

So, P6 and P31M have a few highly similar exemplar pairs:

jaccard %>%
  filter(., Jaccard > .35) %>%

Analyses

jaccard_mod1 <- aov(Jaccard ~ Group, jaccard)
summary(jaccard_mod1)

Average Jaccard similarity scores differ across wallpaper groups, with mean scores for P1 the largest.

Nevertheless, there appear to be a number of exemplar pairs in other wallpaper groups that have especially high Jaccard scores. Lets sort Jaccard indices across the wallpaper groups.

jaccard_plot_2 <- jaccard %>%
  ggplot(.) +
  aes(x = Jaccard, fill = Group) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_grid(Group ~ .)
jaccard_plot_2

jaccard_sort <- jaccard %>%
  dplyr::arrange(., desc(Jaccard)) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(., overall_rank = 1:length(Jaccard))
jaccard_plot_3 <- jaccard_sort %>%
  ggplot(.) +
  aes(x = overall_rank, fill = Group) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_grid(Group ~ .)
jaccard_plot_3

jaccard_mod2 <- aov(overall_rank ~ Group, jaccard_sort)
summary(jaccard_mod2)
##              Df   Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## Group         4  8119014 2029753   30.29 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   945 63328824   67015                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:
